+        #
+        # The eigenvalue has to clear a floor proportional to ||W||, not
+        # merely be positive.  A purely feedforward W is nilpotent, so
+        # its true leading eigenvalue is exactly 0 -- but it is also
+        # defective, and eigenvalues of a defective matrix carry error on
+        # the order of eps**(1/m) for a Jordan block of size m, so SLEPc
+        # converges to a small *positive* value (~1e-5) rather than to 0.
+        # A bare `> 0` test lets that noise through, and alpha =
+        # lambda_max / 1e-5 then inflates W by ~1e4 and hands back
+        # influence scores of ~1e12 with no indication anything is wrong.
+        #
+        # Skipping the rescale is the right answer here, not an error:
+        # W - I is still non-singular and stable for a nilpotent W (every
+        # eigenvalue sits at -1) and the solve returns the exact Neumann
+        # sum.  What it does mean is that lambda_max stops being the
+        # amplification knob it is documented to be, so say so.
+        #
+        # Real recurrent connectomes clear the floor by orders of
+        # magnitude (BANC 0.087, C. elegans 0.175 in these units), while
+        # nilpotent noise lands near 1e-5.
+        fro_norm = W_norm.norm(PETSc.NormType.FROBENIUS)
+        if eig_val_largest > self._EIG_REL_FLOOR * fro_norm:
